Each YAML defines the dataplane configuration for the respective VM.

2️⃣ Dataplane YAML Template (hub-vmX.yaml)
type: Dataplane
mesh: infra
name: hub-vmX          # replace X with 1..5
networking:
  address: <VM_IP>      # replace with the VM's IP
  inbound:
    - port: 8080
      servicePort: 8080
      tags:
        service: runner
    - port: 9090
      servicePort: 9090
      tags:
        service: api
    - port: 7070
      servicePort: 7070
      tags:
        service: auth
  outbound:
    - port: 5681
      service: "*"

Notes:

address → VM IP in your hub network

servicePort → actual port your service listens on

tags.service → service name used in Kuma mesh DNS

outbound → allows access to any service in the mesh

3️⃣ Running the Universal Dataplane on each VM

On each Talos VM, run:

kuma-dp run \
  --cp-address=http://<GLOBAL_CP_IP>:5681 \
  --dataplane-file=/path/to/hub-vmX.yaml

Replace <GLOBAL_CP_IP> with your global control-plane IP (hub CP in your setup).

You can run this as a systemd service on Talos VMs to keep it alive.

4️⃣ Optional: Automating Startup on Talos VMs

Create a systemd unit (on each VM):

[Unit]
Description=Kuma Universal Dataplane
After=network.target

[Service]
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/kuma-dp run --cp-address=http://<GLOBAL_CP_IP>:5681 --dataplane-file=/etc/kuma/hub-vmX.yaml
Restart=always

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

Place YAML in /etc/kuma/hub-vmX.yaml

Enable with: systemctl enable kuma-dp && systemctl start kuma-dp

✅ After this, all services on your hub VMs are mesh-aware, and spokes can resolve them via DNS like:

runner.infra
api.infra
auth.infra

