Ah! Now it makes sense — you want to run the hub “runner” as a Kubernetes deployment in the cluster, instead of running Kuma DP manually on each Talos VM. This is simpler to manage with Helm and keeps your universal dataplane in the cluster.

Here’s a ready-to-use Helm-style deployment for Kuma universal dataplane that you can install in your hub cluster.

1️⃣ hub-runner-deployment.yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: hub-runner
  namespace: kuma-system
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: hub-runner
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: hub-runner
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: hub-runner
          image: kuma/kuma-dp:2.5.1 # match your CP version
          args:
            - "run"
            - "--cp-address=http://kuma-control-plane.kuma-system.svc:5681"
            - "--dataplane-file=/etc/kuma/hub-dataplane.yaml"
          volumeMounts:
            - name: dp-config
              mountPath: /etc/kuma
      volumes:
        - name: dp-config
          configMap:
            name: hub-dataplane
2️⃣ hub-dataplane-configmap.yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: hub-dataplane
  namespace: kuma-system
data:
  hub-dataplane.yaml: |
    type: Dataplane
    mesh: infra
    name: hub-runner
    networking:
      address: "0.0.0.0"
      inbound:
        - port: 8080
          servicePort: 8080
          tags:
            service: runner
        - port: 9090
          servicePort: 9090
          tags:
            service: api
      outbound:
        - port: 5681
          service: "*"

Notes:

address: 0.0.0.0 binds to the pod IP

Ports 8080/9090 are example inbound services; add your real hub services here

Outbound allows talking to all mesh services

3️⃣ Install with Helm (or kubectl apply)

If you’re using Helm, you can convert this into a simple chart. But the quick way:

kubectl apply -f hub-dataplane-configmap.yaml
kubectl apply -f hub-runner-deployment.yaml

✅ After this, your hub runner runs as a universal dataplane in the hub cluster, services are registered in the mesh, and spokes can reach them via Kuma DNS. No need to run DP manually on each Talos VM.

